title: For Sale/Trade:  Three Old Vintage Revolvers for Parts or Repair Project - Rusty Top Break Iver Johnson H&R Forehand etc.
postcontent: Three vintage "project" top-break revolvers.Two are .32 S&W caliber and one is .22LR. I believe the .22 is a Harrington and Richardson and the others are Iver Johnson or Forehand & Wadsworth (most of these brands are clones of eachother and some parts are probably interchangeable). A variety of spare and extra parts are also included. None of these are fully functional right now. Both the .32s are missing 99% of their finish (originally nickel plated). The .22 has most of the finish on the barrel and cylinder but patchy finish on the rest of it. Various wear to various parts.  One of the .32s does lock up and appears to function in double-action if you push the trigger forward, but the hammer doesn't cock in single action. At a minimum it seems like the trigger return spring is bad, maybe the hammer spring or internals are out of alignment preventing the hammer from cocking into single-action. The other .32 has more issues including a missing extractor. Not sure what else it needs, but the internals are also having issues. I don't remember what the .22 revolver needs, but it should be repairable. I will throw in an assortment of small parts that might fit these or similar guns, including some extra grips, hammers, triggers, springs, and "stuff". I haven't checked to see what parts go with what. Since these are probably over 100 years old, I'm selling them "as is" with no guarantees. If you're not a trained gunsmith I would suggest having them inspected by a gunsmith before shooting them. They would also be cool display pieces if you decided not to shoot them and just clean them up.Will need to see PTP / PTC

postcontent: Price is firm, only cash please.What is in the picture is for sale, one mag, a riser on the rail, gun is in excellent condition.While most bullpup rifles have heavy, long trigger pulls, the RFB does not. The Kel-Tec RFB has absolutely the best trigger pull that I have ever felt on a bullpup rifle. The release is crisp, and while measuring right at six pounds on my trigger pull gauge, it felt lighter and was easy to use, making target work very enjoyable.The Kel-Tec RFB is a handy, reliable, and accurate bullpup rifle that packs the full power of the 7.62x51mm NATO cartridge. As of this writing, the retail price is $1500 US, and they are bringing that much, as demand is still outrunning the supply.
